related.description: The San Antonio Silver Stars fired coach Candi Harvey on Saturday, a day after the team lost their sixth straight game and fell to 6-16.

related.title: Harvey fired; Dailey takes over 6-16 squad
related.headline: Harvey fired; Dailey takes over 6-16 squad

article.headline: Goodson, Dydek lead Stars' to third win in a row
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Adrienne Goodson had 17 points and 10
rebounds and Margo Dydek had 15 points and 10 rebounds to lead the
San Antonio Silver Stars to a 63-53 victory over the Houston Comets
on Friday night.

San Antonio (9-16) improved to 3-0 under interim coach Shell
Dailey and is on a season-best winning streak.

Marie Ferdinand added 18 points for the Silver Stars, who had
lost of six in a row and nine of 10 before coach Candi Harvey was
fired last Saturday.

"They know they can (win)," Dailey said. "It just takes one
win, just one success and they know they can do it again. They have
patience and confidence."

Tina Thompson had 16 points and Sheryl Swoopes added 15 for the
Comets (14-9), who had a four-game winning streak snapped. Michelle
Snow had 13 rebounds for Houston.

Swoopes' layup six seconds into the second half gave the Comets
a 33-32 lead, their last of the game.

The Comets got within five points when Thompson made two free
throws with 2:11 left, but Ferdinand's 10-foot jumper made it
60-53.

"We just didn't play well tonight and you can't afford to do
that against a good team like San Antonio," Swoopes said. "It
seemed like the Stars were well prepared for us defensively."

Dydek also tied a season high with seven blocked shots.

"The difference now is that we're having fun," Ferdinand said.
"We're concentrating on the little things now."

Houston was 7-of-36 (19.4 percent) from the field in the second
half and shot 30.2 percent for the game. The Comets were also
12-of-19 from the free throw line.

"When you can't put the ball in the basket, it's tough to win a
basketball game," Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "I can't
remember the last time we missed that many free throws."
